A Project on Exploring Bitcoin Prices¶

In this project, we study Bitcoin’s price dynamics and construct predictive, tradable signals derived from its historical behaviour.
Instead of attempting to forecast exact future price which is highly volatile and non-stationary, we focus on modelling returns and directional trends, translating these signals into algorithmic trading rules.

Our approach is benchmarked against a simple Buy & Hold strategy, with an emphasis on risk-adjusted performance rather than raw prediction accuracy.

Although level-error metrics such as RMSE, MAE, and MAPE are useful for evaluating forecasting models, our primary objective is tradability.
Hence, we use the Sharpe Ratio, a measure of return per unit of risk, as our main performance metric.
A higher Sharpe ratio indicates a more efficient strategy, and our goal is to achieve a Sharpe ratio exceeding that of the Buy & Hold benchmark.

The Sharpe Ratio is defined as:

$$\text{Sharpe Ratio} = \frac{E[R_p - R_f]}{\sigma_p}$$

where

  • $( R_p )$ = portfolio or strategy return,
  • $( R_f )$ = risk-free rate (often assumed 0 for crypto),
  • $( \sigma_p )$ = standard deviation of portfolio returns.

In this academic exercise, we evaluate two trading strategies based on predicted Bitcoin returns:

1. Long Only Strategy¶

This strategy takes a long position (buys Bitcoin) only when the predicted future return is positive:

$\hat{r}_{t+1} > 0 \ \Rightarrow \ \text{Go Long (Buy)}$

and holds cash (no position) when the predicted return is negative:

$\hat{r}_{t+1} \le 0 \ \Rightarrow \ \text{Stay Flat (Sell to Cash)}$

2. Long and Short Strategy¶

This strategy allows positions on both sides of the market:

$\hat{r}_{t+1} > 0 \ \Rightarrow \ \text{Go Long (Buy)}$

$\hat{r}_{t+1} < 0 \ \Rightarrow \ \text{Go Short (Sell BTC)}$

Thus, the model continuously maintains exposure—either long or short—based on its predicted return signal.

For simplicity, we assume no trading fees, slippage, or transaction costs.

Data Selection and Period of Analysis¶

We use daily Bitcoin price data spanning from 2023 to 2025 for this study.

The dataset is divided as follows:

  • Training period: 2023–2024
  • Testing period: 2025

This temporal split ensures that all model training occurs strictly before the evaluation period, preventing lookahead bias or data leakage.

We begin our sample from 2023 to avoid potential spillover effects from the COVID-19 pandemic, which introduced extreme market volatility and structural breaks in earlier years (2020–2022).
By focusing on more recent data, we aim to capture a representative post-pandemic regime of Bitcoin market behavior.

All data are assumed to be chronologically ordered and non-overlapping between training and testing sets.

Stationarity Check: Rolling Statistics and ADF Test¶

Before applying any predictive time series or machine learning models, it is important to understand the statistical properties of the Bitcoin returns series.

In particular, we examine whether the return series is stationary, i.e., whether its statistical characteristics (mean and variance) remain constant over time.

1. Rolling Mean and Standard Deviation¶

We compute and plot the 30-day rolling mean and rolling standard deviation of Bitcoin returns.
This allows us to visually inspect how the average return and volatility evolve over time.

If these rolling statistics fluctuate substantially, it indicates that the series is non-stationary, which may lead to biased model estimates and spurious correlations.

$$\text{Rolling Mean at time } t = \frac{1}{k} \sum_{i=t-k+1}^{t} r_i$$

$$\text{Rolling Std at time } t = \sqrt{\frac{1}{k-1}\sum_{i=t-k+1}^{t}(r_i - \bar{r})^2}$$ where $( k = 30 )$ days.

2. Augmented Dickey–Fuller (ADF) Test¶

To statistically test for stationarity, we apply the Augmented Dickey–Fuller test, which tests the null hypothesis:

$$ H_0: \text{The series has a unit root (non-stationary)} \\ H_1: \text{The series is stationary} $$

  • If the p-value < 0.05, we reject $( H_0 )$ and conclude the series is stationary.
  • If the p-value > 0.05, we fail to reject $( H_0 )$, suggesting the series is non-stationary.

3. Interpretation¶

If the Bitcoin returns are found to be non-stationary, we may need to apply transformations such as differencing, log-returns, or standardization before modeling.
Ensuring stationarity is crucial because most statistical and machine learning models assume that the underlying data distribution does not change over time.

Stationarity Confirmation and Strategy Evaluation¶

Based on the rolling statistics and the Augmented Dickey–Fuller (ADF) test,
we conclude that the Bitcoin returns series is stationary, meaning its statistical properties such as mean and variance remain stable over time.
This is an important property because it ensures that the model can learn consistent patterns without being affected by time-dependent trends or variance shifts.

Now that stationarity has been established, we proceed to define a modular & reusable evaluation function that automates the computation of key performance metrics and plots for our trading strategies.
This function will allow us to systematically compare the effectiveness of different models and trading rules (e.g., Long Only and Long & Short) based on their risk-adjusted returns and predictive accuracy.

In [9]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score

def analyze_model_performance(test_df, y_test, y_pred, model_name='Model'):
    """Analyzes and plots model performance for two trading strategies."""
    
    # Calculate metrics for both strategies
    long_only_returns = np.where(y_pred > 0, y_test, 0)
    long_and_short_returns = np.sign(y_pred) * y_test
    
    long_only_sharpe = (long_only_returns.mean() / long_only_returns.std()) * np.sqrt(252)
    long_short_sharpe = (long_and_short_returns.mean() / long_and_short_returns.std()) * np.sqrt(252)
    buy_hold_sharpe = (y_test.mean() / y_test.std()) * np.sqrt(252)

    y_test_sign = (y_test > 0).astype(int)
    y_pred_sign = (y_pred > 0).astype(int)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_sign, y_pred_sign)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test_sign, y_pred_sign)

    # Print summary
    print(f"--- Performance for {model_name} ---")
    print(f"Sharpe Ratio (Long Only): {long_only_sharpe:.3f}")
    print(f"Sharpe Ratio (Long & Short): {long_short_sharpe:.3f}")
    print(f"Sharpe Ratio (Buy and Hold): {buy_hold_sharpe:.3f}")
    print(f"Directional Accuracy: {accuracy*100:.2f}%\n")
    print("Confusion Matrix:\n", cm)
    print("-" * 30)

    # Plot actual vs. predicted returns
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.plot(test_df['date'], y_test, label='Actual Returns', alpha=0.7)
    plt.plot(test_df['date'], y_pred, label='Predicted Returns', alpha=0.7, linestyle='--')
    plt.title(f"Return Prediction ({model_name})")
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Return")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # Plot cumulative returns for both strategies
    plot_df = test_df.copy()
    plot_df['Long_Only_Return'] = long_only_returns
    plot_df['Long_Short_Return'] = long_and_short_returns
    plot_df['Cum_Actual'] = (1 + plot_df['Next_Return']).cumprod()
    plot_df['Cum_Long_Only'] = (1 + plot_df['Long_Only_Return']).cumprod()
    plot_df['Cum_Long_Short'] = (1 + plot_df['Long_Short_Return']).cumprod()
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.plot(plot_df['date'], plot_df['Cum_Actual'], label='Buy and Hold')
    plt.plot(plot_df['date'], plot_df['Cum_Long_Only'], label='Long Only Strategy', linestyle='--')
    plt.plot(plot_df['date'], plot_df['Cum_Long_Short'], label='Long & Short Strategy', linestyle=':')
    plt.title(f"Cumulative Returns Comparison ({model_name})")
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Cumulative Return")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
                xticklabels=['Predicted Down', 'Predicted Up'],
                yticklabels=['Actual Down', 'Actual Up'])
    plt.title(f'Directional Prediction Confusion Matrix ({model_name})')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Direction')
    plt.ylabel('Actual Direction')
    plt.show()
    
    return {
        'long_only_sharpe': long_only_sharpe,
        'long_short_sharpe': long_short_sharpe,
        'buy_hold_sharpe': buy_hold_sharpe,
        'accuracy': accuracy
    }

Linear Regression Model with 14-Day Lag Features¶

We begin with the most basic predictive model — Linear Regression — to test whether there exists any linear relationship between past Bitcoin returns and future returns.
This serves as a baseline model to examine if short-term patterns (such as momentum or mean reversion) can be captured through simple linear dependencies.

Specifically, we use the past 14 daily returns as lagged explanatory variables to predict the next-day return:

$$ r_{t+1} = \beta_0 + \sum_{i=1}^{14} \beta_i \, r_{t-i} + \varepsilon_t $$

where

  • $( r_{t+1} )$ is the next-day return,
  • $( r_{t-i} )$ are lagged returns from the previous 14 days, and
  • $( \varepsilon_t )$ is the error term.

Justification for the 14-Day Window¶

The 14-day lag captures short-term market dynamics that often reflect momentum or reversal behavior over a two-week period.
This time horizon is widely used in both technical analysis and empirical finance, where short-term momentum typically persists over 5–15 trading days.

Modeling with XGBoost¶

After testing linear regression, we apply XGBoost, a more powerful nonlinear machine learning model based on gradient-boosted decision trees.
Unlike linear models, XGBoost can automatically capture nonlinear patterns, interactions between lagged returns, and threshold effects that may exist in Bitcoin price dynamics.

We use the previous 21 daily returns as input features to predict the next-day return.
This 21-day horizon (about one trading month) helps the model detect both short- and medium-term momentum.

Key properties of XGBoost:

  • Learns complex nonlinear relationships without manual feature engineering.
  • Handles noisy and unscaled data effectively (no need to standardize returns).
  • Uses built-in regularization (max_depth, n_estimators) to reduce overfitting.

How Gradient Boosting Works¶

XGBoost builds a sequence of weak learners (decision trees) $(\{h_m(x)\}_{m=1}^{M})$,
each one improving upon the residuals (errors) of the previous model:

$$ \hat{y}_i^{(m)} = \hat{y}_i^{(m-1)} + \eta \, h_m(x_i), $$

where

  • $(\eta)$ is the learning rate,
  • $(h_m(x))$ minimizes the gradient of the loss function with respect to model predictions.

The objective minimized by XGBoost is:

$$ \mathcal{L} = \sum_i l(y_i, \hat{y}_i) + \sum_m \Omega(h_m), $$

where

  • $(l(y_i, \hat{y}_i))$ is the prediction loss (e.g., squared error),
  • $(\Omega(h_m))$ is a regularization term that penalizes overly complex trees.

Finally, the model’s predictions are evaluated using the same trading strategy framework as before, comparing Long Only, Long & Short, and Buy & Hold performances via Sharpe ratio and directional accuracy.

Neural Networks (ANN) for Next-Day Return Prediction¶

We extend beyond linear/tree models to a feed-forward neural network (ANN) that learns a nonlinear mapping from the past 21 daily returns to the next-day return.
Inputs are lag features $((r_{t-1},\ldots,r_{t-21}))$; the target is $(r_{t+1})$.

Model form $$ \hat{r}_{t+1} \;=\; f_\theta\!\big(r_{t-1}, r_{t-2}, \dots, r_{t-21}\big), $$ where $(f_\theta)$ is a multi-layer perceptron with ReLU activations and dropout regularization.

Loss (training objective) $$ \mathcal{L}_{\text{MSE}} \;=\; \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\big(\hat{r}_{i} - r_{i}\big)^2. $$

Scaling

  • Features $(X)$ and target $(y)$ are MinMax-scaled for stable optimization.
  • Predictions are inverse-transformed back to the original return scale before evaluation.

Hyperparameter tuning (Keras Tuner)

  • Search over hidden units, dropout rates, and learning rate for Adam.
  • Final model is retrained on the full training set with the best hyperparameters.

This ANN captures nonlinear and interaction effects among lags that linear models may miss, while dropout and tuning help control overfitting on noisy daily return data.

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(
        units=hp.Int('units_layer1', min_value=32, max_value=512, step=32),
        activation='relu',
        input_shape=(X_train_scaled.shape[1],)
    ))
    model.add(Dropout(rate=hp.Float('dropout_1', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.5, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(
        units=hp.Int('units_layer2', min_value=16, max_value=64, step=16),
        activation='relu'
    ))
    model.add(Dropout(rate=hp.Float('dropout_2', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.5, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    
    # Using a more appropriate range for learning rates
    hp_learning_rate = hp.Choice('learning_rate', values=[1e-3, 1e-4, 1e-5])
    
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=hp_learning_rate),
                  loss='mean_squared_error')
    return model

Multilayer Perceptron Regressor¶

Similar to the feed-forward neural network (ANN) method, we make want to map the past 21 daily returns to the next-day return using machine learning model multilayer perceptron (MLP) regressor. Inputs are lag features $((r_{t-1},\ldots,r_{t-21}))$; the target is $(r_{t+1})$.

Loss (training objective)

  • For learning and selection of hyperparameters, we made use of the Sharpe Ratio as our metric instead of a convention loss function.

Scaling

  • Features $(X)$ and target $(y)$ are MinMax-scaled for stable optimization.
  • Predictions are inverse-transformed back to the original return scale before evaluation.

Hyperparameter tuning

  • Do a local search over hidden layer sizes, alpha for L2 regularisation term, tolerance level and learning rate for Adam.
  • Final model is retrained on the full training set with the best hyperparameters.

y_train_scaled = y_scaler.fit_transform(y_train.reshape(-1, 1))

# --- 3. Hyperparameter Tuning Setup ---
model = MLPRegressor(random_state=99, max_iter=2000)

# Finding a local optimal hyper parameters using long and short strategy Sharpe Ratio as metric
# Get number of neurons of layers
best_sharpe = -100
best_i = None
best_j = None
for i in range(1, 101):
    for j in range(1, 101):
        model = MLPRegressor(random_state=99, hidden_layer_sizes=(i, j), max_iter=2000)

Sequence Modeling with LSTM¶

We next apply a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) network, which models temporal dependencies by processing a 30-day window of sequential inputs.
Unlike feed-forward networks, the LSTM maintains an internal memory that learns how past market behavior influences future returns.

Input–Target Setup

Let the feature vector at day $t$ be:

$$ \mathbf{x}_t = [\text{btc\_return}_t,\ \text{volatility\_14,t},\ \text{rsi\_14,t}] $$

For each window of $n = 30$ days:

$$ \mathbf{X}_{t-n+1:t} = (\mathbf{x}_{t-n+1}, \ldots, \mathbf{x}_t) $$

The model predicts the next-day return as:

$$ \hat{r}_{t+1} = f_{\text{LSTM}}(\mathbf{X}_{t-n+1:t}) $$

where $f_{\text{LSTM}}$ is the nonlinear mapping learned by the network.

Model Architecture

  • Two stacked LSTM layers (50 units each) with dropout regularization
  • Dense output layer predicting $\hat{r}_{t+1}$
  • Optimizer: Adam  Loss: Mean Squared Error (MSE)

Reason for 30-Day Window

A 30-day lookback (~1 month) captures both weekly momentum and medium-term volatility clustering,
while avoiding the overfitting risk associated with excessively long memory horizons.

Preprocessing

All input features and targets are MinMax-scaled for stable gradient updates.
Predictions are inverse-scaled back to the original return scale before evaluation.

The LSTM provides a more powerful temporal framework that can capture sequence dependencies
and nonlinear relationships that static models may overlook, offering a deeper test of whether Bitcoin returns exhibit any time-dependent predictability.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import LSTM, Dense, Dropout
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

def create_sequences(data, n_steps):
    X, y = [], []
    for i in range(len(data)):
        end_ix = i + n_steps
        if end_ix > len(data) - 1:
            break
        # The input sequence is now all feature columns
        seq_x, seq_y = data[i:end_ix, :-1], data[end_ix, -1]
        X.append(seq_x)
        y.append(seq_y)
    return np.array(X), np.array(y)

rs = gain / loss
data['rsi_14'] = 100 - (100 / (1 + rs))

test_df = data[data['date'].between('2025-01-01', '2025-12-31')]

feature_cols = ['btc_return', 'volatility_14', 'rsi_14']
x_scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
X_train_scaled = x_scaler.fit_transform(train_df[feature_cols])
X_test_scaled = x_scaler.transform(test_df[feature_cols])

y_test_scaled = y_scaler.transform(test_df[['Next_Return']])

Sequence Modeling with Bayesian LSTM with MC Dropout¶

Standard Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) network do not report model uncertainty as it gives a single prediction while with a Bayesian LSTM, we can provide a rnage of possible outcomes. This quantify model uncertainty given Bitcoin problem is a time-series forecasting and uses complex data.

Keeping the LSTM network intact, we introduced Monte Carlo Dropout as an approximate Bayesian inference technique. During training of model, we apply dropout as usual and during validation of our test, we keep the dropout active to get a distribution of our predictions. We take the mean of our distibution for final prediction, providing a more robust and scalable way to estimate the returns.

    Dropout(0.2),

model_lstm.fit(X_train_lstm, y_train_lstm, epochs=50, batch_size=32, verbose=0)

# --- 4. Predict using MC-Dropout and Inverse Scale ---
def mc_dropout_predict(model, X, samples=100):
    """Performs Monte Carlo Dropout predictions."""
    predictions = np.zeros((samples, X.shape[0]))
    for i in range(samples):
        # Make a prediction with dropout ACTIVE by setting training=True
        predictions[i, :] = model(X, training=True).numpy().flatten()
    return predictions

# Get the distribution of predictions
mc_predictions_scaled = mc_dropout_predict(model_lstm, X_test_lstm)

# The final prediction is the mean of the distribution
y_pred_scaled = np.mean(mc_predictions_scaled, axis=0)

# Inverse scale the results
y_pred = y_scaler.inverse_transform(y_pred_scaled.reshape(-1, 1)).flatten()
y_test = y_scaler.inverse_transform(y_test_lstm.reshape(-1, 1)).flatten()


# --- 5. Align DataFrame and Analyze ---
test_df_lstm = test_df.iloc[n_steps:].copy()
# Note: The model name is changed to reflect the Bayesian method
metrics = analyze_model_performance(test_df_lstm, y_test, y_pred, model_name='Bayesian LSTM')

print("\nMetrics dictionary returned by the function:")
print(metrics)

Volatility Modeling with ARMA–GARCH¶

Finally, we employ a hybrid ARMA–GARCH model to capture both the serial correlation and time-varying volatility in Bitcoin returns.
This approach blends autoregressive structure for the mean with conditional heteroskedasticity for the variance — a standard tool in financial econometrics.

Model specification

The return process is modeled as:

$$ r_t = \mu + \sum_{i=1}^{p} \phi_i r_{t-i} + \varepsilon_t, \qquad \varepsilon_t = \sigma_t z_t, $$

with the conditional variance following a GARCH(1,1) process:

$$ \sigma_t^2 = \omega + \alpha_1 \varepsilon_{t-1}^2 + \beta_1 \sigma_{t-1}^2, $$

where $z_t$ are standardized residuals drawn from a Student’s-$t$ distribution.

We also include multiple autoregressive lags ($p=60$) to test whether past returns contain predictive power for the mean process.

Training and testing

  • Train: 2023–2024
  • Test: 2025
  • Returns are scaled by 100 for numerical stability.

The model is fitted using the arch library (mean='ARX', vol='Garch', p=1, q=1, dist='t').

Interpretation of results

From the AR component, we identify several significant lags (e.g., lag 1, 25, and 60).
These lags correspond to daily, weekly, and monthly periodicities,
suggesting that Bitcoin exhibits short-term momentum (1-day), and repeating volatility or return clustering patterns around 25–30 days.

We then refit the model using only these significant lags to focus on the most informative predictors and reduce noise.

Why ARMA–GARCH?

  • AR terms capture predictable patterns in mean returns.
  • GARCH terms capture volatility clustering, a key property of financial series.
  • Together, they provide a dynamic forecast of both expected return and risk over time.

The ARMA–GARCH model reveals that certain days (e.g., lag 1, 25, 60) have statistically significant predictive power, implying
that Bitcoin’s return dynamics exhibit structured temporal dependencies rather than being purely random.

train_returns = data.loc['2023-01-01':'2024-12-31']['btc_return']
test_returns = data.loc['2025-01-01':'2025-12-31']['btc_return']

# Also create a test_df for the analysis function
test_df = data.loc['2025-01-01':'2025-12-31'].reset_index()
test_df['Next_Return'] = test_returns.values

# --- 2. Model Training ---
scaled_train_returns = train_returns * 100

model = arch_model(scaled_train_returns, mean='ARX', lags=60, vol='Garch', p=1, q=1, dist='t')
results = model.fit(disp='off')

# Print the summary to see the new ARMA coefficients
print(results.summary())

# --- 3. Forecasting ---
forecasts = results.forecast(horizon=len(test_returns))

y_pred = forecasts.mean.iloc[-1].values / 100
y_test = test_returns.values

# --- 4. Analysis and Visualization ---
metrics = analyze_model_performance(test_df, y_test, y_pred, model_name='ARMA-GARCH')

print("\nMetrics dictionary returned by the function:")
print(metrics)

Inter-Market Modeling with XGBoost¶

We extend our model to include cross-asset influences from Gold and the S&P 500, recognizing that Bitcoin’s price often reacts to global risk sentiment and safe-haven flows.

We construct a multivariate lag space using 14 days of historical returns for all three assets:

$$ \mathbf{x}_t = [\text{BTC}_{t-1:t-14},\ \text{GOLD}_{t-1:t-14},\ \text{S\&P}_{t-1:t-14}] $$

The model predicts Bitcoin’s next-day return: $$ \hat{r}_{t+1}^{BTC} = f_{\text{XGB}}(\mathbf{x}_t) $$

where $f_{\text{XGB}}$ is a gradient-boosted regression tree ensemble.
By including other markets, we test whether Bitcoin behaves more like a risk-on (correlated with equities) or risk-off (correlated with gold) asset.
The model is trained on 2023–2024 and tested on 2025, using the same trading strategy evaluation via Sharpe ratio, directional accuracy, and cumulative returns.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from xgboost import XGBRegressor

# Assume btc_gold_sp_close_cleaned_returns and analyze_model_performance are defined

# --- 1. Data and Feature Engineering ---
# Select the returns from all three assets
data = btc_gold_sp_close_cleaned_returns[['date', 'btc_return', 'gold_return', 'snp_return']].copy()
data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'])

num_lags = 14 # Let's use 14 days of history for each asset

# Create lagged features for all three assets
for lag in range(1, num_lags + 1):
    data[f'btc_lag_{lag}'] = data['btc_return'].shift(lag)
    data[f'gold_lag_{lag}'] = data['gold_return'].shift(lag)
    data[f'snp_lag_{lag}'] = data['snp_return'].shift(lag)

# Create the target variable (Bitcoin's next-day return)
data['Next_Return'] = data['btc_return'].shift(-1)
data = data.dropna().reset_index(drop=True)

# --- 2. Training and Prediction ---
train_df = data[data['date'].between('2023-01-01', '2024-12-31')]
test_df = data[data['date'].between('2025-01-01', '2025-12-31')]

# Create a comprehensive list of all feature columns
btc_lags = [f'btc_lag_{i}' for i in range(1, num_lags + 1)]
gold_lags = [f'gold_lag_{i}' for i in range(1, num_lags + 1)]
snp_lags = [f'snp_lag_{i}' for i in range(1, num_lags + 1)]
feature_cols = btc_lags + gold_lags + snp_lags

X_train = train_df[feature_cols].values
y_train = train_df['Next_Return'].values
X_test = test_df[feature_cols].values
y_test = test_df['Next_Return'].values

model = XGBRegressor(n_estimators=300, max_depth=4, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# --- 3. Analysis and Visualization ---
metrics = analyze_model_performance(test_df, y_test, y_pred, model_name='XGBoost (Inter-Market)')

print("\nMetrics dictionary returned by the function:")
print(metrics)

Summary of Model Performances¶

Across all models, the MLP Regressor achieved the best performance, with the highest Sharpe ratios for both Long Only (2.218) and Long & Short (2.349) strategies.
This indicates strong nonlinear learning capability and robustness, despite only moderate directional accuracy (55~%). This trend can also be observed for the Tuned ANN (Scaled) model, which delivers competitive results compared to the other models.

Linear and Ridge regressions performed reasonably well, confirming the presence of mild linear structure in returns.
XGBoost (Lagged) offered solid gains over linear models, but its Inter-Market version did not generalize well — suggesting cross-asset effects may not hold consistently out-of-sample.
The ARMA–GARCH model captured some volatility clustering, performing comparably to linear models, while LSTM slightly underperformed, possibly due to overfitting or limited data length. We did not include Bayesian LSTM with MC Dropout in the summuary as the Monte Carlo Dropout is a stochastic process and at every run, we will get a different set of results, resulting in the method being irreproducible.

Overall, machine learning models (XGBoost, ANN, MLP) outperform classical baselines and Buy & Hold in risk-adjusted terms, demonstrating that even weak predictive structure can be exploited for improved Sharpe ratios when managed systematically.
